<title>GCRIO What's New</title>
</head>
<body>
<a href = "http://gcrio.ciesin.org/"><img align = bottom src = "/gifs/gcrio-header.gif"></a><br>
<hr>
<h2>What's New on the GCRIO World Wide Web Server</h2>

<h3>21 November 1996</h3>

<a href="/gwcc/toc.html">Global Warming and Climate Change</a><br>
<blockquote>A publication prepared by researchers in the Department of
Engineering and Public Policy at Carnegie Mellon University to explain the 
issue of global warming and climate change to a general audience.  Issues
addressed include:  The science of global warming; the potential impacts of
climate change, and the range of policy responses to the threat of climate
change.</blockquote>

<a href="/OnLnDoc/unepO3sum.html">Environmental Effects of Ozone Depletion (Executive Summary)</a><br>
<blockquote>This United Nations Environmental Program (UNEP) report comes 
between the Assessments of 1994 and 1998 on the Environmental Effects of
Ozone Depletion.  The Executive Summary presented here confirms previous
research and presents new findings concerning:  Ozone and UV changes; health
effects of ozone depletion; and the effects of ozone depletion on
terrestrial and aquatic ecosystems as well as on biogeochemical cycles and
air quality.</blockquote>

<h3>1 November 1996</h3>
<a href="/educ/EarthEducation.html">Earth Education Site</a><br>
<blockquote>Educators and students will want to bookmark this one! The scope and arrangement
 of this collection make navigation easy and provide links to lesson plans,
 classroom activities and resources(some free!), catalogs, professional
 organizations, federal agencies, non governmental organizations, conferences,
 libraries and other educational tools. <a href="/educ/Features.html">
Features</a> a
series of articles, connects to exceptional teachers, cutting edge scientists
and researchers or trailblazing environmentalists to augment global change and
environmental education. Future plans include an interactive capability that
will enhance global communication and foster global education.</blockquote>

<h3>30 October 1996</h3>
<a href="/USGCRP/sustain/toc.html">Sustainable Development and Global Climate Change: Conflicts and Connections</a>
<blockquote>Proceedings of a conference sponsored by the Center for Environmental Information, Inc., Dec
4-5, 1995, in Washington, D.C. Climate change scientists addressed the following topics:
<dl>
<dd>SESSION I. The Climate Change Phenomenon and Sustainability
<dd>SESSION II. Sustainability and Climate Change: Impacts, Adaptation and Mitigation Options
<dd>SESSION III. Sustainable Development and Climate Change: Economic Assessment
<dd>SESSION IV. Sustainable Development and Climate Change: Science for Policy in the Face of Uncertainty
</dl>
</blockquote>


<h3>21 October 1996</h3>
<a href="/CONSEQUENCES/introCON.html">CONSEQUENCES - The Nature and 
Implications of Environmental Change</a>
<blockquote>The second issue of CONSEQUENCES Volume 2 contains review articles
entitled, "Ending Hunger:  Current Status and Future Prospects;" "Impacts of
Introduced Species in the United States;" and "Population Policy:  Consensus
and Challenges."</blockquote>
 


<h3>7 September 1996</h3>
<a href="/ocp97/toc.html">
<dt><a href="/ocp97/toc.html">Our Changing Planet - The FY 1997 US Global 
Change Research Program</a>
<blockquote>An annual report by the Committee on Environment and Natural Resources 
(CENR) of the National Science and Technology Council (NSTC).  <i>Our 
Changing Planet</i> describes the US Global Change Research Program for FY 1997. 
Federal Agency activities and funding levels are presented.
</blockquote>
 
<h3>23 August 1996</h3>
<a href="/USGCRP/CENR/proguide96/toc.html">
       Program Guide to Federally Funded Environment and Natural Resources R&D</a>
<blockquote> The Program Guide provides information on the types of research and
development activities that are supported by
       Federal agencies in the area of environment and natural resources, the
mechanisms used by agencies to select R&D
       recipients of Federal R&D dollars, and potential funding opportunities.</blockquote>

<h3>30 July 1996</h3>
<a href="index.html">GCRIO Home Page</a>
<blockquote>Our home page has been redesigned!  We have streamlined and reorganized our web space to make information retrieval easier.  Information on the role
of Federal agencies and organizations in the US Global Change Research Program 
(USGCRP) and the Global Change Data and Information System (GCDIS) has
been added.  Our search capabilities have been improved and we have included a
Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) page.  You can request documents from the GCRIO through our online document request form.  Our Educational Resources section 
has 
been expanded greatly with the addition of EarthRise and other links.  More 
improvements are coming in the next few months.  Check back often and see!
</blockquote>

<h3>15 May 1996</h3>
<a href="/CONSEQUENCES/introCON.html">
        CONSEQUENCES - The Nature & Implications of Environmental Change</a>
<blockquote>The first issue of CONSEQUENCES Volume 2 contains review articles
entitled, "Remembrance of Things Past:  Greenhouse Lessons from the Geologic
Record;" "How Bountiful are Ocean Fisheries;" and "The Sun and Climate."
</blockquote>
<h3>16 April 1996</h3>

<a href="/ocp96/index.html">
 Our Changing Planet:  The FY 1996 U.S. Global Change Research Program</a>
<blockquote>A supplement to the President's fiscal year 1996 budget, Our 
Changing Planet is an overview of the U.S. Global Change Research Program 
(USGCRP).  This overview summarizes recent research on seasonal to 
interannual climate fluctuations; climate
 change over the next few decades; stratospheric ozone depletion and 
increased UV radiation; and changes in land cover and in terrestrial and 
marine ecosystems.  Included in Our Changing Planet are highlights of 
recent research results and agency and program
 budgets for FY 1996.</blockquote>

<h3>6 March 1996</h3>

<a href="/geo/title.html">
Geological Indicators of Rapid Environmental Change:  An International Checklist</a>
<blockquote>As a contribution to integrated environmental/ecological
monitoring and state-of-the-environment reporting, the
International Union of Geological Sciences (IUGS) through its
Commission on Geological Sciences for Environmental Planning has
developed the first version of a checklist of geoindicators.
These have been compiled as tools for tracking changes in the
dominantly abiotic components of forest, aquatic, desert,
coastal, polar, mountain and other terrestrial ecosystems.</blockquote>

<h3>15 January 1996</h3>

<a href="http://www.unep.ch/ipcc/ipcc95.html">
Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) Second Assessment Report</a>
<blockquote>The 1995 Second Assessment Report from the IPCC will be published soon.  
The IPCC has made the Synthesis Report, and the Summaries for Policymakers for all
 three working groups, available for on-line reading and downloading from the
United Nations Environment Program web site.</blockquote>

<h3>8 January 1996</h3>

<a href="/CSP/webpage.html">U.S. Country Studies Program Home Page</a>
<blockquote>The U.S. Country Studies Program provides support for climate change
studies and climate change national action plans to developing
countries and countries with economies in transition. These pages
contain information on current US CSP projects, workshops, and technical
document resources.
</blockquote>

<h3>3 January 1996</h3>

<a href="/CONSEQUENCES/introCON.html">
        CONSEQUENCES - The Nature & Implications of Environmental Change</a>
       <blockquote>The third issue of CONSEQUENCES Volume 1, contains 
articles entitled:  "The Environment Since 1970" and "Climate Models:  How Reliable are their Predictions?"</blockquote>

